# Code Style and Structure Rules

## Class Responsibility

Each class should map to one of the architecture's named responsibilities (see `architecture.mdc` and `ARCHITECTURE_Detailed.md`). Do not let a class accumulate responsibilities outside its stated role — e.g. `BuffSystem` owns Apply decisions and Tick lifecycle, not damage calculation or input handling. If a method you're adding doesn't fit the class's responsibility, it belongs somewhere else.

`AbilityBase` is the only abstract base class in this project. Do not introduce new abstract base classes — if behavior needs sharing, use an interface plus a private helper method.

## Naming Conventions

| Category | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Interfaces | `I` prefix, PascalCase | `IEvent`, `IAbility`, `IBuffEffect`, `IBuffApplier`, `IDamageModifier`, `IRandomProvider`, `IAbilityTargetProvider`, `ICooldownQuery`, `IEventBus`, `IReadOnlyStatCollection` |
| Abstract classes | `Base` suffix | `AbilityBase` |
| ScriptableObject configs | `Config` suffix | `AbilityConfig`, `BuffConfig`, `PlayerConfig`, `EnemyConfig` |
| MonoBehaviour adapters | No suffix | `Player`, `Enemy`, `GameManager` |
| Event structs | `Event` suffix | `DamageEvent`, `BuffAppliedEvent`, `EntityDiedEvent`, `StatChangedEvent` |
| Context types | `Context` suffix, both `readonly struct` (see `type-design.mdc`) | `DamageContext`, `AbilityContext` |
| Dependency bundles | `Deps` suffix, `readonly struct` | `AbilityTargetDeps` |
| Slot types | `Slot` suffix | `AbilitySlot` |
| Result types | `Result` suffix, `readonly struct` | `AbilityExecuteResult`, `TryExecuteResult` |
| Enums | PascalCase, no suffix | `StatType`, `StatModifierType`, `DamageType`, `AbilityFailReason` |
| Private fields | `_camelCase` with underscore prefix | `_owner`, `_handlers` |
| Public properties | PascalCase | `CurrentHealth`, `MaxHealth` |

## Formatting and C# Style

Follow the conventions in `Core/Events/IEvent.cs`, `IEventBus.cs`, and `EventBus.cs`.

**Braces and control flow**
- Allman style: opening `{` on its own line.
- Always use braces for `if` / `else`, even for single-line bodies.
- Prefer early return for guard clauses and no-op paths instead of deep nesting.

**File layout**
- `using` directives at the top, blank line, then block-scoped `namespace` matching the layer folder (e.g. `Core.Events`, `Gameplay.Stats`).
- Order `using` directives in consecutive groups (no blank lines between groups):
  1. BCL / `System.*` — alphabetical
  2. Unity (`UnityEngine`, `UnityEditor`, …) — alphabetical
  3. Other third-party (e.g. `NUnit.Framework` in tests) — alphabetical; omit when unused
  4. Project namespaces — **by assembly layer** (dependency direction, bottom → top), then alphabetical within the same layer prefix:
     `Core` → `Gameplay` → `Ability` → `Demo` → `Tests`
- Place `using static` directives after project usings (alphabetical).
- Do not mix groups; when adding usings, match this layout rather than relying on IDE reorder alone.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;
using Core.Events;
using Gameplay.Combat;
using Ability.Buff;
using Ability.Config;
```

**Blank lines**

Prefer fewer blank lines. Use a blank line when a **complete control-flow block** ends or the member kind changes — not after every statement.

Same section (no blank line between):
- Consecutive same-kind members (fields, thin proxy properties, one-line assignments such as `?? throw`)
- A member and its `//` comment (`//` sits on the line above; that does **not** start a new section)
- A **single-line** local and the `if` / `return` that immediately consumes it
  (e.g. `AbilitySlot slot = …;` then `if (slot.Config == null)`, or `Execute(…);` then `if (executeResult.Succeeded)`)

```csharp
public readonly DamagePipeline DamagePipeline;
// Only for reading cooldowns. AbilitySystem owns CooldownManager.
public readonly ICooldownQuery CooldownQuery;
// Roll crit here. Pipeline just reads DamageContext.IsCrit.
public readonly IRandomProvider RandomProvider;

public ICombatEntity TargetEntity => Target.Entity;
public IEventBus TargetEventBus => Target.EventBus;
public IBuffApplier TargetBuffApplier => Target.BuffApplier;

AbilityConfig config = _configs[abilityIndex];
IAbility ability = _abilities[abilityIndex];

AbilityExecuteResult executeResult = ability.Execute(in context);
if (executeResult.Succeeded)
{
    ...
}
```

New section (one blank line):
- Field block → property block → constructor / methods
- After a **multi-line** `if` / `else` / `foreach` / `try` block (`}`), before the next statement — including the assignment or call that the guard protects
- Between consecutive independent `if` guards (e.g. range check then zero no-op)
- After an early-return / early-exit block, before the happy-path body or return
- Between unrelated validation groups when they are not adjacent multi-line `if`s already covered above (e.g. ctor: target checks vs remaining `?? throw` deps)

```csharp
if (abilityIndex < 0 || abilityIndex >= _abilities.Length)
{
    throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(nameof(abilityIndex));
}

AbilityConfig config = _configs[abilityIndex];
IAbility ability = _abilities[abilityIndex];

if (duration < 0f)
{
    throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(...);
}

if (duration == 0f)
{
    return;
}

_stateByIndex[abilityIndex] = new CooldownState { Remaining = duration, Duration = duration };

if (duration <= 0f)
{
    return 0f;
}

return GetRemaining(abilityIndex) / duration;
```

Do **not** blank-line after every member, between a `//` and the next field in the same group, or between a single-line local and the `if` that immediately inspects it.

- End each file with a single trailing newline.

**Locals and initialization**
- Use `var` when the type is obvious from the right-hand side.
- Prefer target-typed `new()` for field/collection initialization (e.g. `new Dictionary<Type, Delegate>()`).

**Null checks and exceptions**
- Required arguments: `if (arg == null) { throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(arg)); }`
- Use `nameof(...)` in exception constructors.
- Use pattern matching where it clarifies intent (e.g. `if (del is not Action<T> action)`).
- Multi-line `throw` is allowed when the message is long; use `$"..."` interpolation for dynamic values, not `+` concatenation.
- See `error-handling.mdc` for fail-fast categories and Stats validation.

**Documentation** — see `documentation.mdc` (single source of truth for XML / inline comment tiers). Do not restate those rules here.

**Types**
- Concrete implementations not meant for extension: `public sealed class`.
- Private fields: `_camelCase`; use `readonly` when the reference does not change after construction.

## Folder Structure

Four gameplay layers under `Scripts/` (former Character / Combat / Buff folders are merged into **Gameplay/**):

```
Assets/
├── Scripts/
│   ├── Core/                ← IRandomProvider, StateMachine, IState
│   │   └── Events/          ← IEvent, IEventBus, EventBus only (no gameplay event structs)
│   ├── Gameplay/            ← shared gameplay (stats, combat, …)
│   │   ├── Combat/          ← Damageable, ICombatEntity, DamagePipeline, DamageContext, Modifiers/
│   │   │   └── Events/      ← HealthChangedEvent, HealEvent, DamageEvent, EntityDiedEvent
│   │   ├── Stats/           ← StatCollection, Stat, StatModifier, IReadOnlyStatCollection, StatType, StatModifierType
│   │   │   └── Events/      ← StatChangedEvent
│   ├── Ability/             ← AbilitySystem, AbilityType, AbilityFactory, AbilitySlot, IAbility, AbilityBase, IAbilityTargetProvider
│   │   ├── Abilities/
│   │   ├── Buff/            ← IBuffApplier, BuffConfig, BuffSystem (when implemented)
│   │   ├── Config/
│   │   ├── Cooldown/        ← CooldownManager, ICooldownQuery (namespace Ability.Cooldown)
│   │   ├── Events/          ← CooldownStartedEvent, CooldownEndedEvent
│   │   └── Result/          ← AbilityExecuteResult, TryExecuteResult, AbilityFailReason
│   └── Demo/                ← GameManager, Player, Enemy, PlayerInputHandler, NoOpBuffApplier, UnityRandomProvider, PlayerConfig, EnemyConfig, StatBaseEntry, DashAbility, EnemyAI, states, PlayerHUD / EnemyHUD
├── Tests/
├── Materials/
└── Scenes/
    └── Demo.unity
```

Do not place types in the wrong layer folder (e.g. a Gameplay type under Core/). Do not recreate `Character/`, `Combat/`, or `Buff/` as top-level Script folders. Do not create speculative empty subfolders.

**Config ScriptableObject placement:** `AbilityConfig` and `BuffConfig` live in **Ability/** (`Config/` and `Buff/`). `PlayerConfig` and `EnemyConfig` live in **Demo/** — they apply base stats via `ApplyBaseStats(StatCollection)` at entity init, plus Player **`List<AbilitySlot>`** (`Config` + `AbilityType`). Demo may wrap `AbilityFactory` (e.g. `DemoAbilityFactory`) to create Demo-only skills such as `DashAbility` without reverse dependencies into Ability.

## Assembly Definitions

Each folder under `Scripts/` has its own `.asmdef`. Names follow `Game.<LayerName>`:

| Folder | Assembly name | References |
|---|---|---|
| Core/ | `Game.Core` | (none) |
| Gameplay/ | `Game.Gameplay` | Core |
| Ability/ | `Game.Ability` | Core, Gameplay |
| Demo/ | `Game.Demo` | Core, Gameplay, Ability |
| Tests/ | `Game.Tests` | Core, Gameplay, Ability (not Demo); Editor-only test refs |

Dependency direction is one-way downward: **Core ← Gameplay ← Ability ← Demo**. Do not introduce reverse references.

Do not place code from one assembly into another assembly's folder. Do not create new `.asmdef` files without a concrete dependency-isolation reason (a future `Game.Editor` for editor-only tooling would qualify). Update this table if you do.
